review_blob: Color: a golden orange.  White lacey head.  Aroma: pine and wild flowers, very much a floral scent.  A mild beginning that gets stronger as it moves back and zaps you with a strong bitter zest (hops).  Sam Adams says its an "explosion" of hops, they werent kidding.   I respect this beer, I am not the biggest hop head so it was a little intense for me, but it was good.
overall this beer was not what I expected, it is a little light in body, I was expecting a little heavier flavor as well.  An ok beer, there are much better doubles out there.

the color of the beer is the color of any normal porter, the smell is of something different though.  Instead of smelling undertones of coffee and chocolate, I smell yeast typical of belgian ales.  There are chocolate and coffee flavors in this beer but it is the yeast that surprises me.   Good beer, not like most porters, but good.

A strong belgian wit that is highly carbonated with a complex flavor that releases more and more as you go through it.  Its a strange marriage of wine and beer that works well.  A good complex full bodied wit.

pours a white head, initial quaf of bitter hops, however after first taste you get the sweetness typical of most hefeweizens however with a slight crisp bitter aftertaste typical of a pure pilsner.  An odd pairing, but thats the best I can explain it.  A good hefeweizen  I enjoy and would buy on occasion when I see it around.
This is an excellent everyday beer during the winter.  Offers a nice nose of malt with a wonderful nut flavor with a hint of cinnamon in the aftertaste.

A great beer, this dunkelweizen has a great aroma of wheat and malt.  For a malt fan, this is a good beer.  It creates a nice off- white head, amber in color, you smell nuts and get a fruit aftertaste.  Basically an excellent wheat beer with a little more flavor.
I smell and taste the smoked peat and caramel malt.  There is an aftertaste of spice which leaves a warm feeling on the tongue as you swallow.  My first Divine Reserve, but it wont be my last!
